{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_horsetail_ver01/data/sn86075141/00340582044/1945082301/0720.xml":{"full_text":"fij\nMontana Labor New# 4\nVOL BEND YOUR\nGET IN ON THE MIGHTY\nV/\nG\nSEVENTH IVAR LOAN.\nMONEY.\nTHEY GIVE THEIR LIVES! V\nHEIJP SPEED VICTORY\n\nPUBLISHED WEEKLY IN THE INTERESTS OF ORGANIZED LABOR\nd\n^-/vvvv v v vv\\-!*v\nBUTTE, MONTANA, THURSDAY, AUGUST 2:5, 1945\nXXI\nNo. 25\n\n\nVETERAN GETS\nFINANCIAL AID\nTO RUN HATCHERY\nST, IGNATIUS, Aug, 22\u2014Harold S.\nOtter, 37, ex-air corps mechanic, should\nbe the envy of every fisherman in Mon\ntana because he not only literally iwades\nin rainbow trout on his 53-acre com\nmercial fish hatchery located four and\none-half miles north of here, but he can\ndip a fly into Post creek bordering his\nplace and catch his limit any day.\nThrough the veterans' self-employed\nreadjustment allowance setup which is\nadministered by the Montana unemploy\nment compensation commission for the\nveterans' administration, Otter will be\nable to maintain himself for at least one\nyear until his new venture, a business\nof his own, begins to produce rainbow\ntrout for commercial consumption.\n\"I am happy to say that through the\nself-employed allowance I am receiving\neach month, I will be able to live until\nmy hatchery starts producing on a vol\nume basis,\" Otter said.\nMore than 85 other ex-servicemen are\ndrawing or have drawn self-employed al\nlowances since the inception of the pro\ngram in September 1944, the commission\nannounces. Discharged servicemen or\nwomen may obtain information con\ncerning this phase of the G. I. bill by\ninquiry at any public employment office\nMontana or by writing the commission's\nHelena office.\nOtter bought the Post Creek hatchery\nfrom John S. Dishman, who has retired,\nand who is financing the deal. Dish\nman said he was glad to turn Over his 1\nbusiness to a veteran, to help him get I\nstarted anew, and urged others who wish\nto retire to do the same. For this rea-\nson. Otter was able to purchase the\nspread, but did not have operating capi- I\ntal which is not being supplied by the 1\n$100 allowance he receives monthly from\nthe government. This is provided under\nprovision of Title V of the servicemen's\nreadjustment act of 1944, some times\ncalled the G. I, bill. In the event of\nany net earnings during any one month I\nhe will receive the difference between\n$100 and his earnings.\nThe former air corps mechanic served j\nnine months in the Army before being\ndischarged for medical disability. Pre\nvious to his service, he had been a\ncaterer in Milwaukee and Chicago. He\nis married and has three children. He\nwas discharged in July, 1043, and worked\nfor a time for a defense sub-contractor\nin Billings as a machinist. He pur -1\nchased the hatchery June 9 and has j\nsince been working his new property.\nj\nPower equal to the work performed by\n8.000,000 men laboring steadily for 10\nyears was turned out by Grand Coulee\nDam during the war, the Bureau of Re\nciamation announced today in telling\nhow the world's greatest dam helped j\nGRAND COULEE'S\nWAR RECORD\nspeed victory.\nProm the time that the first generator j\nwent into production on March 22, 1941,\nseveral months before Pearl Harbor, to\nthe surrender of Japan on August 14,\nthe power plant at Grand Coulee Dam j\ntumed out 15,767,474,000 kilowatt-hours\nof energy. Great blocks of this power j\nwent to the famed atomic bomb plant at\nHanford. Wash.\nSave waste fats! Save waste paper!\nBoth are essential.\nBILBONIC PLAGUE\n'5Kni iA Aiedm\nEv=\nJuly \u00ce3, 19k5\n\nPvt. t. L\u00bbvln\u00ab, 3 S 6 .U 32 I\nMedic*! iVtacPenr. t, rirooke Conv,\nFort ^ouater.,\nDear ^rlne\u00ab\n\nfour iotUr of July 19 ho* just two rtc\u00ablv\u00abd ux 1 1\nconfess to you that I took tins to reed the asinine c intents\nof your letter, from your eerlbhlings 1 get strong eueplclon\nthat you \u00abr\u00bb s 'Boeery innate\" fron the slue sections of \u00abe\u00bb Kork\nCity end that you ere what Is coesconly called s eery comson \"kike\",\ndo you nerlt Senatorial attention,\nBut you \u00bbake euch an ugly threat until I trdnk i will juet\ntry your hand Mid call you what 1 think you are\u2014juet a sorry,\npuny, insignificant, wicultured, unrefined, dirty, pusillanimous,\nllmlcolous, coMauiiielic braying Jackass. If this does not fit you\ndoes not paint your true picture, then let me know and i will\n,ae you i can do better word painting,\nsure if you want to give publicity to this letter the public\ngenerally will recognize your photograph.\nTherefore, you lo rot deeerv\u00ab\nr r\nfinish the Job oecause 1 promi\n\nserry for you and i suggest that you sub\ntil tc irsatner t of even a seccr.d-clsss psychiatrist.\nBut reajJy,\nri\\h rauch sympathy,\nlours\nU. S, S.\n76b: -i\nThis letter, to an American soldiers and former member of the National Mari\ntime Union (CIOi, is the latest specimen of Senator TheexKire Bilbo's (D.\n-Miss.) poison-pen campaign to be made public. It is a reply to criticism of\nthe polltaxer's notorious My dear Dago\" letter tb Miss Jo\u00bbepii',ie P -ol\u00fc\n''M\nTHE WASHih\nU\nSCENE\nBy Federated Press\nj\n\nI of figures on forthcoming Jobless\nj ness released here August 14 predicted\nseven million out of work by Christmas\nin the transition from war to peacetime\nUnemployment Compensation Can't\nSolve Job Problems Alone\nWASHINGTON,\u2014(FPi\u2014One cOmpila\nemployment.\nThis seven million figure is the work\nI \u00b0f economists of separate agencies, and\nthe men said they believed a figure of\nj eight or nine million may be reached\n\nin 194\u00ab.\nAgainst this official release filtered\nthrough the red tape of the OWI news\nj desk, your reported has seen a more\ncomplete set of figures made up by still\nanother agency that must remain un\nmentioned\u2014which sets 10 million as the\nestimate for December. 1945, and says\nthat four million of these will be out of\nwork by September.\nThe most re-assuring thing about\nboth sets of statements is that they\nagree that this mass unemployment \"will\nnot be alarming\" if it is only temporary.\nSure to feel the impact of this wave\nof unemployment at full flood will be\nDetroit and Seattle among the larger\ncities\u2014and such war boom towns\nPascagoula, Miss., with its giant ship\nyards. and Huntsville, Ala., with Its\ntextiles.\ncountm f the temporary workers, wives\nand transient wU1 looking\nor a \u00a3ob by tbe end of ,hc y ear 1\u00bb\ncities the \"8 ure wil h '8 h r\nThat total of 10 million is only three\nmllllon short o\u00a3 the low point of the\nHoover depression when we had 13 mil\nOverall, the unpleasant prospect Is\nthat one in ten U. S. breadwinners (not\nlion jobless back In 1932.\nNow that the crisis has come, the\nvarious federal agencies are in a dither\nissuing anonymous estimates of the size\nof the army of unemployed. Those esti\nmates were available, if they could be\npried loose, months and months ago.\nBut OWI. the National War Labor Board,\ntlie Stabilization Director and other key\nagencies and individuals felt it would\n\"not be too good\" for the morale of the\npublic to let them be printed.\nHad the figure been announced, it is\npossible that Congress could have been\nforced to remain in Washington and do\nsomething about reconversion, about un\nemployment compensation and the full\nemployment bill.\nToday we have the prospect ot the\nHouse ways and means committee being\ncalled back to Washington for hearings\nopening August 21 on the Truman plan\nto extend and expand unemployment\ncompensation to cover federal and mari\ntime workers and set a uniform figure\nof $25 a week for 26\nChairman Robert L. Doughton (D.-N. C.)\nagreed to the hearings after a session\nwith Truman at the White House. He\nveeks.\nis not an advocate of unemployment\ncompensation of any kind\u2014and certainly\n[is no friend of the Truman proposal,\nUndoubtedly pressure from Truman\nand the Democratic administration will\nforce this tory\nport out a bill written largely along the\nline suggested. It is highly likely that\nit will be adopted in the face of the\nunrest caused throughout the nation by\nthe mounting joblessness.\nBut the real danger will come after\n(Continued on Page Three)\nloaded committee to re\nIC MAHTan linn\nIS MONTANA A DEAD DUCK?\nYes, Montana is a dead duck and the Montana Stand\nard, which is one of the nine subsidized newspapers of the\nA. C. M. chain, would have you believe Montana is up and\ncoming. Montana is being held back by the A. C. M. Com\"\npany and for no other reason but that this company wants\nto continue in control so it can gouge the citizens of Mon\ntana, as it has been doing for the past fifty years. They\nwant no new industries in this state for, with new indus\ntries, there would be a greater number of workers and\nthese workers, in turn, would become voters of this state\nand if they were not working for the A. C. M. Company,\nthey would vote against the interests of the company and\nthe company knows tins to he a fact. If we had large in\ndustries in the eastern part of the state last general elec\ntion. the labor party would have elected all of their can\ndidates.\nIt gives ns a laugh when they say: \"Montana, on the\nother hand, is just getting a good start toward the attain\nment of her place in the sun as a self-sufficient, progressive\nand prosperous entity.\" How about the prosperity in\nButte, Montana How about the prosperity in other Mon\ntana communities? How about the prosperity in all of\nMontana?\nAnother statement made by the editor of the Montana\nStandard is; \"It should be remembered that Home wasn't\nbuilt in a day, that only 75 years ago the Indians were still\na menace in Montana.\" What a joy it would be to the citi\nzens of Montana if we had the Indians back. The A. C. M.\nCompany tried their damndest to recruit the Indians of\ntins state to work in their mines and smelters during the\npast years but the Indians were too wise for these big\nmogels. All they could get out of the Indians was a bis\n\"heap-no-good,\" and they went back to their reservations\nWise Indians. And the dumb white men are leaving this\nstate also, in droves, and are going to other places where\nthey can live, like white people. Can we have prosperity?\nJobs? It's very doubtful.\nThe A. C. M. Company thinks it will have the service\nmen and women to fill their mines with cheap labor after\ntile war. liiere JS every evidence the \"copper collared' V\nllOVS tire victims of their own propaganda. The men and\nwomen in our armed forces and those in war production\nA-OT-I r ivr W, WTTiAvrci iT-ii\n\u25a0AKhi I> V -NG MljANS anti-union and anti-labor. The\narmed forces will not forget the A. C. M. Company and\ntheir WIRE DE AL If we have anvthintr to do with it\n\u2022it \\TArii 1 11 rt\nWC Will NUL let the armed forces, or anyone else, forget\nthis deal.\nI\nWE WILL NOT HAVE PROSPERITY IN THIS\nSTATE TILL THE A. (I M. COMPANY IS CUT LOOSE\nfrom control of our state legislature,\nOFFICERS, STATE INSTITUTIONS AND\nCITY AND COUNTY OFFICIALS,\nmen, they are determined to get something DECENT for\nthemselves and their people when they return to civilian\nlifV. And they know they cannot find it in Montana under\ntlie present setup. They simply won't go for it. But\nthere will be plenty of jobs for them when the MVA gets\nunder wav. And it will get under way in spite of all the\nA. C. M. Company does to hinder it. These men have seen\nthe abundance America can produce. They have seen, or\nheard about, the TVA or tin* huge power dams of the West,\nabout the Public Housing Authority, about the slums that\nwere cleared, the roads that were built, the millions of\njobs that were provided by the government during dtr\npression, and they know, with their future and that of\ntheir families at stake, that is not a healthy situation to\nline ui> against public works programs nor any steps the\ngovernment may take to guarantee full employment. And\nthe vets will be the decisive political force in our country\nfor the next 25 years. They may serve the best interests!the\nof our country as well in peace as they did in war.\nIs Montana a dead duck? Quack-quack-quack. And\na big quack to the Montana Standard and its editor and\nthe other \"quack\" newspapers of the state of Montana.-\u2014\nAnaconda Smeltermen's Voice.\nSTATE\nAs to lhe service\nMONTANA LABOR\nCONVENTION\nGETS UNDER WAY\nBILLINGS. Aug, 21 .\u2014Delegates fron\u00bb\n51 organizations affiliated with the\nMontana Federation of Labor, holding its\nannual state convention here, heard wel\ncoming addresses by Mayor H. E. Bid\ndinger, Charles T. Trott and Thomas C.\nColton at its opening session Tuesday.\nThe convention, which is expected to\nlast through Thursday, is being con\nducted to establish postwar plans, to\nformally elect officers and to settle !abor\ndisputes and grievances.\nJames D. Graham, executive president\nof the Montana federation, responded to\nthe welcome. J. E. Winsby, assembly\ntrustee, was chairman for the opening\nsession.\nMonday evening the executive board,\nconsisting of nine members, met to con\nsider problems confronting the organi\nzation and to make detailed plans for\nthe three-day event.\nA canvassing board selected by Gra\nham. began counting the ballots for new\nofficers Tuesday afternoon. These bal\nlots had been cast by mall earlier in\nthe year and were held until the\n(Continued on Page Pour)\nJAPANESE LEADER\nSAYS DEMOCRATIC\nSPARKS STILL ALIVE\nNEW YORK\u2014(FP)\u2014Are the Japanese\npeople capable of uprooting their fascist\nleaders and building a democratic Japan\nwith Allied help? Insight into that\nquestion was given in an interview Israel\nEpstein, Allied Labor News correspond\nent, had last year with Shushumu Okano,\nleader of the Japanese People's Eman\ncipation League, which has its head\nquarters in Yenan, China.\n\"Undoubtedly there is anti-war feeling\namong a section of the Japanese people,\nbut It is not yet common,\" Okano told\nEpstein. \"The majority of he people\nare still deceived by the militarists. If\nit were not so. Japan would present a\ndlffei ent picture today\nOkano pointed out, however, that while\nover-estimation of the anti-war move\nment in Japan might lead 'o er. -on, to\nIgnore it and the possibilities of democ\nacy in Japan would be far worse. The\nbasic fact, he stated, is that this war\nis \"against the interests of the Japanese\npeople themselves, and their only hope\nlies in an Allied victory in which they\nparticipate by fighting the mlli\nContinued on Page 4)\nnnri/V-iUNDERSECRETARY\none world and j\nLABOR I\nlhe coming peace he will be cut off\nrom u s war material which he had\nl>een count,in 8 on for his war against the\nnorth CWna libe rat ed areas\n\nWelcome Back to Jail\nThe 8 rou P \u00b0f exiled Argentine labor\nleaders Wh0 recently dedded to return\nto their country because of \"the reiter\nated pledges of the Argentine govern\nment concerning civil liberties\" were\nwarned on arriving in Buenos Aires har\nbor that they would be imprisoned if\nthey went ashore, Allied Labor News\nreports.\nBy Federated Press\n\nsome significant developments, particu\nlarly in China where C'hlang Kai-shek\nseized, On the occasion to threaten war!of\nagainst China's Communist-led partisan\narmies.\nThis is no surprise to observers of the\nChinese political scene, particularly\nsince the conflict between the Chung\nking government and guerrilla China\u2014\nwhich at its most quiet has been an\narmed truce\u2014flared out into the open\nagain a month ago in Shensi province\nwhen fascist Gen. Hu Tsung-nan at\ntacked 8th route guerrilla army troops.\nBut apparently Chiang Kai-shek,\nwhose whole war policy has been to\ntreat the guerrillas as more dangerous\nenemies than the Japanese, now is seek\ning an excuse for a full-fledged milil\ntary campaign against the guerrillas.\nThe latest clash came when Com\nmunist Gen. Chu Teh mistook the first\nconditional Japanese surrender offer for\nthe real thing and ordered Japanese\ntroops to surrender and hand over their\narms to the guerrillas. Chiang Kai-shek\nquickly came back with an order to the\nJapanese not to surrender to the Com\nmunists and warned the guerrillas to\ntake no \"independent\" action.\nThe bulk of the Japanese army is north\nof the Yangste river and in Manchuria.\nThat's where most of the guerrillas are\ntoo and that's where most of the serious\nfighting has been going on. From his\nsafe vantage point in the south, Chiang\nnow publicly expresses his fears that\nthe Japanese and thousands of Chinese\npuppet troops will surrender to what he\nconsiders the wrong kind of Chinese.\nCivil War In China?\nAll the whoop-la that followed Japan's\ninitial offer to surrender turned up\nHe is also anxious to prevent Japa\nnese weapons from falling into the hands\nof the guerrillas, particularly since with\nattempt on Hitter's nie. After July\n20 1944, the nu ber of p\u00b0 lltica i arrests\nincreased tremen ous>\nAccordingly, they returned to Monte\nvideo. Among them were Luis Victor\nSomml of the Woodworkers Union and\nPedro Tadioli, secretary of the Buenos\nAires Labor Federation,\nence heightened the skepticism with\nwhich Argentine exiles view the govern\nment's action in lifting the state of\nsiege, which has suppressed all demo\ncratic activities since December 1941.\nTheir experl- I\n1,300 a Day\nAccording to Gestapo records un\nearthed in Germany recently, 205,000\narrests were made during the first half\nof 1944 in Germany proper.\nOne hundred and forty-six thousand\nof these arrests were made because of\n\"labor evasion and slowdowns\" and the\nremaining 69,000 because of dissemina\ntion of defeatist rumors, listening to for\neign broadcasts, political and religious\nopposition to the Nazi regime, etc.\nThis means that about 1,300 persons\nwere arrested dally. That was before\nA secret anti-labor plot by the Falange\nhas been exposed by the labor newspa\nper, Hoy, in Havana, Cuba, Allied labor\nNews reports. The paper published a\nprotostatic copy of a secret circular,\nissued by a group of big businessmen,\nannouncing an ambitious plan of the\nFalange to attack the government, de- 1\nstroy the Cuban Federation of Workers\nand set up corporative worker-employ\ner unions similar to those In Franco\nSpain. The campaign is to lie fought\nunder the slogan of \"anti-communism.\"\nTruman to Ask for\nPermanent U. S.\nEmployment Agency\nWASHINGTON\u2014(FP)\u2014A recommen\ndation that Congress make the U. S.\nEmployment Service a permanent feder\nal agency will be made shortly by Pres.\nHarry S. Truman, a reliable source told\nFederated Press August 14.\nThis action, slated for delivery in an\n.early message on the subject, will be a\nb]ow \u00eftate g rights bloc n Con\ngreSfi that had hoped that USES and\nunemployment compensation legislation\nwould be returned to the individual states\nw dea with on a local basls\nSAVE YOUR\nBLUE STAMPS\nBlue ration points are no longer neces\nsary In obtaining processed foods. How\never, Chester Bowles urges you to pre\nserve your blue-ration stamjis as there\nis a possibility they may be used to sup\nplant red ration points later.\nJ. C. GREW RESIGNS,\nothers may quit in the near future\nEUROPEAN RIGHT-WINGERS CONDEMNED\nWASHINGTON.\u2014(EP)\u2014Emperor Hirohito, when he\nsays his prayelrs these days, should, ask a special blessing\nfor Joseph C. Grew. For it was Grew, as undersecretary\nof state, who did more than anv other individual to save\n1 iuu lu SdVL\n_ .M IKcKlO trOUl going the W<1V ot MuSSOUlli, and, ]HTllHj)S,\nHitler,\nGrew has resigned because\nA11 Onlon Central Committee of soviet\nTrade Unions. He said. Extremely in\nterestlng information has been ex -1\nRanged and a n\u2122 basis has been laid\nfor strengthening and cementing the re-1\nlations between organised labor in the\nO. S. and the Soviet Union. This friend\nship between the working people of these\ntwo important nations would be the\ngreatest assurance for a durable and\nlasting peace.\"\nNOTICE\nTlie next meeting of the Silver\nBow Trades Labor Council will\ntake place September 11.\nCIO WILL SEND\nCOMMITTEE\nTO SOVIET RUSSIA\nWASHINGTON.\n(FP) Ten Soviet\nlabor union representatives who have\nbeeen touring the U. S. as guests of CIO\nPres. Philip Murray, were honored at a\nfarewell reception held at the embassy\nof the USSR Aug. 14, with a large group\nof national labor leaders invited.\nThe embassy reception followed by\nfeme hours the appearance of Murray\nand Chairman Vasslli Kuznetsov of the\nRussian delegation at the White House,\nThe two spent a quarter hour with Pies.\nHarry S. Truman in the midst of the\nrushing preparations for V-J day.\nAs the Soviet visitors prepared to re\nturn home after visiting war plants,\nunion meetings and individual workers\nin scores of cities, President Murray an\nnounced that the CIO will send an offi\nclal delegation to visit the Soviet Union\n\"at a very early date.\"\ntended by Kuznetsov, chairman of the\nMurray accepted the invitation ex\nThe CIO leader revealed that forma\nAmerican-Soviet Trade Union\ntion of\ncommittee is being considered and will\nbe brought up for action before the\nofficial bodies of the CIO and the Rus\nsian unions.\nKuznetsov, commenting on the dele\ngation's visit here, said that on the\nbasis of its contacts \"we are convinced\nthat the CIO is the progressive Ameri\ncan trade union movement.\"\nHe thank the CIO leaders for their\n\"fraternal reception\" and added he be\nlieved the visit \"will be a valuable con\ntribution to the cause of cementing\nfriendship between the workers of the\nU. S. and the USSR.\"\nRation-Free Sale of Shoes\nto Continue Through Oct. 13\nThe ration-free sale of men's and\nwomen's low-priced shoes began August\n17th, and will continue through October\n13th, 1945, OPA has announced. The\ndate was advanced from August 27th,\nto enable the public to take advantage\nof any summer shoes meeting the re\nquirements for ration-tree sale.\nOnly shoes selling for $3.50 or less\nmay be sold ration-free under the order.\nm v MORE WAR BONDS TODAY.\nEMPLOYMENT LEVEL SINCE 1918\nMm ions\nrsv\nCONGRESS Will\nCONSIDER FULL\nEMPLOYMENT BILE\nAFTER RECESS\n\n,iL\nm\n\ny#\nm\nj TABOR SUPPLY\n\nJOBS BECAME\nPLENTIFUL AS\nBOOM PERIOD\nREACHED PEAK\n\ny\nBi>\nt MPIQYMI NT 1\n\n\nV\ny\ny\nFROM 1933 TO\nPRESENT DATE\nAN ALMOST UN\nBROKEN RISE\nIN EMPLOYMENT\nPT\u00bbV\nA\nFOLLOWING\nWORLD WAR I\nEMPLOYMENT\nDROPPED\nSHARPLY\nDEPRESSION\nPERIOD SAW\nCOUNTRY'S\nSEVEREST\nUNEMPLOYMENT\n\u00fc\u00e4 0 T\nH/tJ\n[E 33 KI\u00dc\nJobs for all and full peacetime production are necessary if U. S. is to avoid\nthe boom and depression which followed World War I APL and CIO demand\npassage of the Full Employment bill, urged by President Truman.\nand there are some reports this is a sign\nof an impending shakeup in the U. S.\nState department. It may be but\nJoe Crew's job has been completed be\ncause he did what he set out to do. He\nsaved the emperor of Japan.\nIt was Grew who forced our OWI\nbroadcasts to avoid even the most casual,\nunfavorable mention of Hirohito in our\nI psychological warfare. OWI could damn\nTojo, and war-lords and the industri\nalists, but Hirohito was a word that wax\nstrictly banned by OWI\u2014on State de\npartment orders.\nNext to resign from the State depart\nment may be James ra>nn, assistant\nsecretary in charge of European affairs.\nIf we follow the Grew pattern, Dunn\nmay leave only after we have safely\nassured the future of his great and good\nfriend, Francisco Franco of Spain. Dunn\nhas been the most forthright apologist\nfor the European right wing in the\nentire administrative setup in Washing\nton. He Is bitterly anti-left and he con\nsiders anyone a red who suggests that\nFranco, King George II of Greece, or\nKing Peter of Yugoslavia might not be\nable to measure up to the democratic\nideals of their peoples.\nAnother State department fixture\nlikely due for a resignation announce\nment is our ambassador to the Vatican\u2014\nMyron C. Taylor.\nSome good sources here say President\nTruman is highly displeased with Tay\nlor's attitude toward his post and that\na number of Congressmen who have\nbeen in Rome in the recent past, have\nreported angrily to the White House that\nTaylor seemed to be the representative\nof some other power than the U. S.\nPUBLIC INVITED TO\nRETRIEVER TESTS\nRetriever trials at Fullmer's lake in\nElk Park next Sunday are attracting\nmany of the best dogs in the West.\nGoing all out in the way of supporting\nsports, the pioneer Anglers' club\u2014first\nfish and game bird reproductionists in\nMontana\u2014invite all lovers of hunting\ndogs to attend next Sunday's show with\nout admission charge. Benches will be\nunder shade trees and near fireplaces.\nFacilities invite all interested to come\nand stay all day. Springer trials will\nstart at 8:30 a. ra. Moving pictures In\ncolor will 'be taken of all events by that\nardent and veteran sportsman, Bill\nSweet.\nFullmer lake is deeper than ever be\nfore for next Sunday's retriever classic.\nRetrievers are barred from practice in\nthe area until the trials to avoid all\npossible false scents.\nClub President M. E, Buck and Secre\ntary Bill Snyder announce two state\ntrapshooting champions\u2014Nick Berrer of\nSheridan and Joe Latimgr of Butte\u2014will\nbe official shooters of birds throughout\nthe trials.\nThe highway will be well marked and\nthere will be plenty parking space avail\nable together with such added conven\niences as rest rooms, benches under the\nshade trees where suitable fireplace will\nbe at the disposal of those who care to\nuse them. Sandwich and hot dog slants\n(Continued on Page Four)","height":"20166","width":"14454"}}
